PacketWyrm licensing
=====================

PacketWyrm is split-licensed. Which licence applies depends on which part of
the tree a file lives in, because the software stack and the FPGA gateware are
independent works with different obligations.

  Software (host stack)          MIT                     see LICENSE.sw
    sw/**                          -- daemon, CLI, libpacketwyrm, proxyd
    tools/**, configs/**, docs/**  -- helper scripts, examples, documentation

  FPGA gateware (own HDL)        CERN-OHL-S-2.0          see LICENSE.rtl
    rtl/phase3/**                  -- PacketWyrm data-plane / control RTL
    fpga/**                        -- Vivado project, constraints, build glue

  Vendored dependency (submodule, unmodified)
    rtl/phase2/vendor/taxi/**    CERN-OHL-S-2.0          fpganinja/taxi upstream

Why the split
-------------
The RTL under rtl/phase3 is synthesised together with the Taxi 10G MAC/PCS
(rtl/phase2/vendor/taxi, a git submodule) into a single bitstream. Taxi is
licensed under the CERN Open Hardware Licence Version 2 - Strongly Reciprocal
(CERN-OHL-S-2.0), whose reciprocity applies to a conveyed "Product" (the
gateware/bitstream) and to Made-Available modified Source. PacketWyrm's own
HDL is therefore licensed under the same CERN-OHL-S-2.0 so that distributing
the combined design or bitstream is reciprocity-clean.

The host software (sw/**) is a separate work: it communicates with the card
over PCIe/BAR and is neither a modification of the Taxi Source nor a Product
made from it, so the hardware licence does not reach it. It is offered under
the permissive MIT licence (LICENSE.sw). The published .deb package ships this
software only (no bitstream), so the release artifact is MIT-licensed in its
entirety.

This file is informational; the authoritative licence texts are LICENSE.sw
(MIT) and LICENSE.rtl (CERN-OHL-S-2.0). SPDX identifiers: MIT and
CERN-OHL-S-2.0.
